label: diaeresis
description: A [diacritic](#diacritic) ( ¨ ), typically placed over a [vowel](#vowel) letter. Depending on the language, it usually either indicates that the vowel is sounded separately from the preceding vowel (as in French [_naïf_](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/na%C3%AFf#French) (“naive”) and the dated English spelling [_coöperate_](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/co%C3%B6perate#English)), or that the vowel has a different (often specifically [fronted](#front_vowel)) pronunciation compared with the base vowel without the diaeresis. The latter usage is typical of [German](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_language) and certain other [Germanic languages](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germanic_languages), as in [_über_](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%C3%BCber#German) (“over”) and [_König_](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/K%C3%B6nig#German) (“king”), and in this case the diacritic often goes by the alternative name of [_umlaut_](#umlaut).

label: ellipsis
description: The omission of a word or phrase that can be inferred from the context.
